properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and ice pellets becoming mixed with rain Thursday night. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm. Maximum wind gusts: easterly 80 km/h. Locations: all of Prince Edward Island, with greatest snowfall amounts expected over Prince County. Time span: Thursday afternoon through Friday morning. Remarks: Snow will develop across the island late Thursday afternoon and will likely mix with or change to ice pellets and rain for a time on Thursday evening, especially over Queens and Kings counties. Precipitation will taper to a few flurries or showers on Friday morning. Strong easterly winds will also develop Thursday afternoon and evening, giving reduced visibilities in blowing snow for some locations. Motorists should anticipate poor driving conditions late in the day Thursday and Thursday night, possibly carrying over into Friday morning in some areas. In addition, strong easterly winds will cause higher than normal water levels along the northern coast during high tide Thursday evening and Thursday night. Ice rafting is also possible along some east- facing parts of the coast. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels with large waves are expected near the coast. Storm surge Warning for Thursday morning. Warning of potential coastal flood conditions issued jointly by Fisheries and Oceans Canada (Science) and the Meteorological Service of Canada - Quebec Area on the 2020-02-06. An intense low pressure system from the United States will bring strong to high winds over the regions specified below. These winds combined with the fact that we are currently in a period of mid-amplitude tidal range could produce minor flooding along the coast near theses localities, on the dates and at the times specified (Eastern Standard Time). Quebec City: 2020-02-27, from 7:00 am to 10:00 am. ### Coastal flooding is possible along the shoreline. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Lake effect snow squalls with widespread blowing snow possible Thursday afternoon through Saturday. Conditions are favourable for snow squalls to develop off Lake Huron Thursday afternoon. A couple of these snow squalls may become particularly intense causing heavy snow and blowing snow well inland of Lake Huron. While the snow squalls will move with time, this snow squall event is expected to last until Saturday morning. Travel will become hazardous, and people are advised to consider changing their travel plans accordingly. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
